{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502741"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:49:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:49:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1895"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1895","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1895"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.4,0.02,0.54,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1895"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51977"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1895","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1895"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1895"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37280"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1215"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2770"},{"type":"tags","id":"2877"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"11093"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3098"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3467"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3973"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11112"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13455"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14909"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42422"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43108"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44815"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51977"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old woman presents due to a loss of hand function, involving finer grip function and dropping crockery, which has worsened over the last 2 years. She has an aching discomfort in both hands, persisent fatigue and a non-pruritic rash over her face.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has a long history of recurrent and intermittent stiffness and pain, particularly in the small joints of her hands, which she self-treats with over-the-counter pain medications. Recently, the joint pains have become resistant to OTC pain medications. Pain and stiffness are worse when she wakes up in the morning but improve as the day progresses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVitals are within normal ranges. Physical examination of the right hand reveals a deformity of the digits as shown (image) with ulnar deviation of the metacarpophalangeal joints, which are correctable with physical manipulation. There is no synovitis of the small joints palpable. Circular erythematous patches are noted on the patient\u0027s cheeks and ears.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory studies reveal mild normocytic anaemia and an erythrocyte sedimentation rate of 45 mm/h (normal: \u0026lt;30 mm/h). There are positive anti-Ro, anti-dsDNA and ANA antibodies. X-rays of the affected joints confirmed the visible deformities, with no underlying bone erosions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chondrocalcinosis","Rheumatoid arthritis","Osteoarthritis","Systemic lupus erythematosus","Psoriatic arthritis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe changes seen in the hand shown in the photograph are those that make up the swan-neck deformity. There is a flexion deformity of the distal interphalangeal joint and resultant hyperextension of the proximal interphalangeal joint. This tends to occur if the lateral slips of the extensor tendon (which inserts into the base of the distal phalanx) stop functioning and the central slip over-compensates in trying to extend the joint, leading to hyperextension of the proximal joint.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic lupus erythematosus \u003C/strong\u003E(SLE) is usually non-erosive arthropathy that can present with an intermittent, symmetric polyarthritis, commonly affecting the hands, wrists and knees. While swan-neck deformity and ulnar deviation are typically associated with rheumatoid arthritis, the distinguishing feature in this presentation is the reversible deformity with physical manipulation, indicating Jaccoud\u0027s arthropathy, seen in SLE. The patient\u0027s non-itchy circular plaque-like rash is suggestive of \u0027discoid lupus\u0027, a common cutaneous manifestation. Patients with SLE may also have several other symptoms (eg, butterfly malar rash, photosensitivity, oral ulcers, Raynaud phenomenon, and cardiopulmonary symptoms). Anti-dsDNA antibodies are highly specific for SLE, and ANA antibodies have a very high sensitivity. As an inflammatory condition, ESR levels are typically elevated and patients may have a normochromic, normocytic anaemia (anaemia of chronic disease). Anti-Ro antibodies are commonly seen in patients with cutaneous lupus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid arthritis \u003C/strong\u003E(RA) is the most common cause of swan-neck deformity. The other hand deformities usually associated with RA are Boutonniere deformity (proximal interphalangeal joint flexion and distal interphalangeal joint hyperextension), ulnar deviation, and the \u0022piano key\u0022 sign (subluxation of the ulna dorsally). Similarly to SLE, as an inflammatory condition, RA can present with a mild anaemia (anaemia of chronic disease), elevated ESR and positive auto-antibodies. Anti-CCP is the antibody with the highest specificity for RA. RF is positive in 70-80% of RA patients, but is often positive in other inflammatory and auto-immune conditions (e.g. SLE) or in patients who are otherwise well. RA is not associated with positive ANA, anti-dsDNA or anti-Ro antibodies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChondrocalcinosis \u003C/strong\u003E(also known as \u0027pseudogout\u0027) the accumulation of calcium pyrophosphate crystals, most commonly affecting the knees and wrists. It rarely can affect the 2nd and 3rd MCP joints when occurring secondary to haemochromatosis, but does not affect the PIP or DIP joints. It is unlikely in this instance, given recurrent episodes of arthritis, in the absence of acute inflammation, in the small joints of the hands.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoarthritis \u003C/strong\u003Eis caused by chronic \u0022wear-and-tear\u0022 of the joints. It is associated with nodular osteophyte development in the distal and proximal interphalangeal joints (termed Heberden and Bouchard nodes, respectively). It is unlikely to manifest with relapsing-remitting joint pains, and the ESR would likely be normal. OA is not associated with swan neck or ulnar deviation deformities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsoriatic arthritis \u003C/strong\u003Ecan present with asymmetric joint pains. However, findings of joint destructions typically include pencil-in-cup deformities of the distal interphalangeal joints on X-ray, dactylitis, and arthritis mutilans. Swan-neck deformity is not typically seen. The plaque psoriasis rash, tends to affect the elbow, knees and lower back, rather than the face. Plaque psoriasis also tends to be itchy or painful, while discoid lupus lesions are not.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE) can cause a symmetrical small joint polyarthritis with correctable deformities and is distinguished from RA by the presence of distinctive cutaneous rashes and a specific autoantibody profile."],"references":["Apostolopoulos D, Hoi AY. Systemic lupus erythmatosus - When to consider and management options. Aust Fam Physician. 2013 Oct;42(10):696-700.","Toyama S, Tokunaga D, Tsuchida S, Kushida R, Oda R, Kawahito Y, Takahashi K. Comprehensive assessment of alterations in hand deformities over 11 years in patients with rheumatoid arthritis using cluster analysis and analysis of covariance. Arthritis Res Ther. 2021 Feb 27;23(1):66. doi: 10.1186/s13075-021-02448-4.","Sharif K, Sharif A, Jumah F, Oskouian R, Tubbs RS. Rheumatoid arthritis in review: Clinical, anatomical, cellular and molecular points of view. Clin Anat. 2018 Mar;31(2):216-223. doi: 10.1002/ca.22980."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37280"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1895"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"12524"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"12524","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/12524"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8ec0d063-826e-421c-8a2c-60872350faeb.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8ec0d063-826e-421c-8a2c-60872350faeb.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":391}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37280"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-31T15:21:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-31T15:22:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1895"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51977"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"a